Implement the `restore/2` controller action in `SoftCrudWeb.DocumentController`. It backs
`POST /api/documents/:id/restore` and must un-delete a soft-deleted document.

It receives the `conn` and the request params, from which it should pull the `"id"`. Look the
document up with `SoftCrud.Documents.get_document/2`, passing `include_deleted: true` so that a
soft-deleted document is actually found (the whole point of this endpoint). Use a `with` so that
an `{:error, :not_found}` falls through to the `action_fallback` controller, which renders a 404
with `{"errors": {"detail": "Not found"}}`.

Once the document is found, restore it with `SoftCrud.Documents.restore_document/1`. That function
always returns `{:ok, document}` — it clears `deleted_at`, and when the document was never
soft-deleted it is a no-op that hands the document back unchanged — so this call can be matched
directly against `{:ok, restored}`. Finally render the `:show` template with the restored document,
producing a 200 response with the standard `{"data": {...}}` payload. Do not add
`include_deleted` query-param parsing here; this action always includes deleted documents.

